bio.text:
Nothing was ever quite the same after [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink]. The band's second album, 1991's Nevermind, revolutionized popular music by bringing alternative rock above ground, introducing mainstream audiences to sounds and concepts that had previously existed only in shadowy record store corners and on low-frequency college radio airwaves. Nevermind's noisy, dissonant guitar rock, mumbled or howled surrealistic lyrics, and generally angsty punk attitudes were unlikely candidates for chart success, but the band undercut their grungy songs with enough pop melodicism to create a sound unlike anything average listeners had ever heard before, striking at the exact right moment to become an unprecedented success.
Since [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] were rooted in an indie aesthetic but loved pop music, they fought their stardom while courting it, becoming some of the most notorious anti-rock stars in history. They consciously attempted to shed their audience with 1993's abrasive, [wimpLink artistId="4297699"]Steve Albini[/wimpLink]-produced third album [wimpLink albumId="77610844"]In Utero[/wimpLink], but vocalist/guitarist/songwriter [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Kurt Cobain[/wimpLink]'s growing mental health and substance abuse issues led to his death by suicide in 1994. Though [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink]'s story was cut tragically short, their legacy stands as one of the most influential in rock & roll history.
[wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Kurt Cobain[/wimpLink] (vocals, guitar) met [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Chris Novoselic[/wimpLink] (born [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Krist Novoselic[/wimpLink]) (bass) in 1985 in Aberdeen, Washington, a small logging town 100 miles away from Seattle. While [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] came from a relatively stable background, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink]'s childhood had been thrown into turmoil when his parents divorced when he was eight. Following the divorce, he lived at the homes of various relatives, developing a love for [wimpLink artistId="3634161"]the Beatles[/wimpLink] and then heavy metal in the process. Eventually, American hardcore punk worked its way into dominating his listening habits and he met [wimpLink artistId="14845"]the Melvins[/wimpLink], an Olympia-based underground heavy punk band. [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] began playing in punk bands like Fecal Matter, often with [wimpLink artistId="14845"]the Melvins[/wimpLink]' bassist [wimpLink artistId="7199913"]Dale Crover[/wimpLink]. Through [wimpLink artistId="14845"]the Melvins[/wimpLink]' leader, Buzz Osborne, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] met [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink], who also had an intense interest in punk, which meant that he, like [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink], felt alienated from the macho, redneck population of Aberdeen. The duo decided to form a band called the Stiff Woodies, with [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] on drums, [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] on bass, and a rotating cast of guitarists and vocalists. The group went through name changes as quickly as guitarists, before deciding that [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] would play guitar and sing. Renamed [wimpLink artistId="14824"]Skid Row[/wimpLink], the new trio featured drummer Aaron Burkhart, who left the band by the end of 1986 and was replaced by [wimpLink artistId="11642487"]Chad Channing[/wimpLink]. By 1987, the band was called [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink].
[wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] began playing parties in Olympia, gaining a cult following. Around 1987, the band made ten demos with producer [wimpLink artistId="3941507"]Jack Endino[/wimpLink], who played the recordings to Jonathan Poneman, one of the founders of the Seattle-based indie label Sub Pop. Poneman signed [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink], and in December of 1988, the band released its first single, a cover of [wimpLink artistId="4358139"]Shocking Blue[/wimpLink]'s "Love Buzz." Sub Pop orchestrated an effective marketing scheme, which painted the band as backwoods, logging-town hicks, which irritated [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] and [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink]. While "Love Buzz" was fairly well-received, the band's debut album, [wimpLink albumId="68639771"]Bleach[/wimpLink], was what got the ball rolling. Recorded for just over $600 and released in June 1989, [wimpLink albumId="68639771"]Bleach[/wimpLink] slowly became a hit on college radio, due to the group's consistent touring. Though [wimpLink artistId="12765826"]Jason Everman[/wimpLink] was credited as a second guitarist on the sleeve of [wimpLink albumId="68639771"]Bleach[/wimpLink], he didn't appear on the record; he only toured in support of the album before leaving the band at the end of the year to join [wimpLink artistId="34477"]Soundgarden[/wimpLink] and then Mindfunk. [wimpLink albumId="68639771"]Bleach[/wimpLink] sold 35,000 copies and [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] became favorites of college radio, the British weekly music press, and [wimpLink artistId="17551"]Sonic Youth[/wimpLink], [wimpLink artistId="13925"]Mudhoney[/wimpLink], and [wimpLink artistId="13542"]Dinosaur Jr.[/wimpLink], which was enough to attract the attention of major labels.
In July 1990, [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] recorded "Sliver"/"Dive" with [wimpLink artistId="13925"]Mudhoney[/wimpLink] drummer [wimpLink artistId="5461934"]Dan Peters[/wimpLink] on drums and producer [wimpLink artistId="11563362"]Butch Vig[/wimpLink]. The band also made a six-song demo with [wimpLink artistId="11563362"]Vig[/wimpLink], which was shopped to major labels, who soon began competing to sign the group. In August, they hit the road with [wimpLink artistId="17551"]Sonic Youth[/wimpLink]'s [wimpLink albumId="77637466"]Goo[/wimpLink] tour (including [wimpLink artistId="7199913"]Crover[/wimpLink] on drums). That September, [wimpLink artistId="5948383"]Dave Grohl[/wimpLink], formerly of the D.C.-based hardcore band [wimpLink artistId="3647078"]Scream[/wimpLink], became [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink]'s drummer and the band signed with DGC for $287,000. [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] recorded their second album with [wimpLink artistId="11563362"]Vig[/wimpLink], completing the record in June of 1991. Nevermind was released in September, supported by a quick American tour. While DGC was expecting a moderately successful release, in the neighborhood of 100,000 copies, Nevermind immediately became a smash hit, quickly selling out its initial shipment of 50,000 copies and creating a shortage across America. What helped the record become a success was "Smells Like Teen Spirit," a blistering four-chord rocker that was accompanied by a video that shot into heavy MTV rotation. By the beginning of 1992, "Smells Like Teen Spirit" had climbed into the American Top Ten and Nevermind bumped [wimpLink artistId="606"]Michael Jackson[/wimpLink]'s much-touted comeback album [wimpLink albumId="19193427"]Dangerous[/wimpLink] off the top of the album charts; it reached the British Top Ten shortly afterward. By February, the album had been certified triple platinum.
[wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink]'s success took the music industry by surprise, [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] included. From the moment [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] were met with mainstream visibility, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] used his newfound fame to relentlessly push his favorite independent artists as if their music was more important than his own. This took the form of bringing Japanese alt-pop trio [wimpLink artistId="3692195"]Shonen Knife[/wimpLink] on tour, covering lesser-known but formative artists like [wimpLink artistId="4206587"]the Wipers[/wimpLink], [wimpLink artistId="3503618"]the Vaselines[/wimpLink], and [wimpLink artistId="8249187"]Meat Puppets[/wimpLink], or wearing a homemade [wimpLink artistId="14850"]Daniel Johnston[/wimpLink] t-shirt during television appearances and high-profile concerts. [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink]'s enthusiastic fandom introduced untold numbers of [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] fans to artists they most likely wouldn't have known to seek out on their own, and in the process, energized those artists' careers.
It soon became apparent that [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] wasn't quite sure how to handle its success. Around the time of Nevermind's release, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] appeared on MTV's Headbangers Ball in drag; the group mocked the tradition of miming on the BBC's Top of the Pops, with [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] constantly throwing his bass into the air and [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] singing his live vocals in the style of [wimpLink artistId="9738333"]Ian Curtis[/wimpLink]; and their traditional live destruction of instruments was immortalized on a Saturday Night Live performance that ended with [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] and [wimpLink artistId="5948383"]Grohl[/wimpLink] sharing a kiss. By early 1992, questions began to arise about the band's stability. [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] married [wimpLink artistId="11159"]Courtney Love[/wimpLink], the leader of the indie rock/foxcore band [wimpLink artistId="3501486"]Hole[/wimpLink], in February of 1992, announcing that the couple was expecting a child. A few months later, [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] canceled several concerts and refused to mount a full-scale American tour during the summer. [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] complained that he was suffering from chronic stomach troubles, which seemed to be confirmed when he was admitted to a Belfast hospital after a June concert. While he went through these problems,DGC released the odds-and-ends compilation [wimpLink albumId="94436656"]Incesticide[/wimpLink] late in 1992; the album reached number 39 U.S. and number 14 U.K.
As [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] prepared to make their third album, they released "Oh, the Guilt" as a split single with [wimpLink artistId="11360"]the Jesus Lizard[/wimpLink] on Touch & Go Records. Choosing [wimpLink artistId="4297699"]Steve Albini[/wimpLink] ([wimpLink artistId="3565255"]Pixies[/wimpLink], [wimpLink artistId="3565238"]the Breeders[/wimpLink], [wimpLink artistId="3868885"]Big Black[/wimpLink], [wimpLink artistId="11360"]the Jesus Lizard[/wimpLink]) as their producer, they recorded [wimpLink albumId="77610844"]In Utero[/wimpLink], in two weeks during. Februrary 1993. Later in the year, reports, including an article in Newsweek, circulated that DGC was unhappy with the forthcoming album, and making accusations that [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] deliberately made an uncommercial record. Both the band and the label denied such allegations. Deciding that [wimpLink artistId="4297699"]Albini[/wimpLink]'s production was too flat, [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] decided to remaster the album with [wimpLink artistId="9366"]R.E.M.[/wimpLink] producer [wimpLink artistId="6196828"]Scott Litt[/wimpLink], who also remixed the singles "Heart Shaped Box" and "All Apologies." [wimpLink albumId="77610844"]In Utero[/wimpLink] was released in September of 1993 to positive reviews and strong initial sales, debuting at the top of the U.S. and U.K. charts. [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] supported it with an American tour, hiring former [wimpLink artistId="4282049"]Germs[/wimpLink] member [wimpLink artistId="4070426"]Pat Smear[/wimpLink] as an auxiliary guitarist. While the album and the tour were both successful, sales weren't quite as strong as expected, with several shows not selling out until the week of the concert. As a result, the group agreed to play MTV's acoustic Unplugged show at the end of the year, and sales of [wimpLink albumId="77610844"]In Utero[/wimpLink] picked up after its December airing.
After wrapping up their U.S. tour on January 8, 1994 with a show at Center Arena in Seattle, [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] embarked on a European tour in February. Following a concert in Munich on February 29, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] stayed in Rome to vacation with [wimpLink artistId="11159"]Love[/wimpLink]. On March 4, she awakened to find that [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] had attempted suicide. When he returned to Seattle, his mental illness grew worse. [wimpLink artistId="11159"]Love[/wimpLink] and [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink]'s management organized an intervention program that resulted in [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink]'s admission to the Exodus Recovery Center in L.A. on March 30, but he left the clinic on April 1, returning to Seattle. His mother filed a missing persons report on April 4. On April 5, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink] died by suicide at his Seattle home.After his death, [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Kurt Cobain[/wimpLink] was quickly anointed as a spokesman for Generation X, as well as a symbol of its tortured angst.
[wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] and [wimpLink artistId="5948383"]Grohl[/wimpLink] planned to release a double-disc live album at the end of 1994, but sorting through the tapes proved to be too painful, so [wimpLink albumId="2570671"]MTV Unplugged in New York[/wimpLink] appeared in its place. The album debuted at the top of the British and American charts, as a home video comprised of live performances and interviews from the band's Nevermind era, titled Live! Tonight! Sold Out!, was issued at the same time (the project began prior to [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink]'s passing and was completed by surviving bandmembers). In 1996, [wimpLink albumId="2570671"]MTV Unplugged in New York[/wimpLink]'s electric counterpart, [wimpLink albumId="634556"]From the Muddy Banks of the Wishkah[/wimpLink], was released, debuting at the top of the U.S. charts. Following [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink]'s death, [wimpLink artistId="5948383"]Grohl[/wimpLink] formed [wimpLink artistId="2753"]the Foo Fighters[/wimpLink], releasing their self-titled debut album in 1995, followed by [wimpLink albumId="33816889"]The Colour and the Shape[/wimpLink] in 1997 and [wimpLink albumId="12269509"]There Is Nothing Left to Lose[/wimpLink] in 1999. [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] formed the trio Sweet 75, releasing their debut in the spring of 1997, and also appeared along with former [wimpLink artistId="3604053"]Dead Kennedys[/wimpLink] frontman [wimpLink artistId="3888570"]Jello Biafra[/wimpLink] and former [wimpLink artistId="34477"]Soundgarden[/wimpLink] guitarist [wimpLink artistId="7420547"]Kim Thayil[/wimpLink] on the 2000 live set [wimpLink albumId="5564061"]Live from the Battle in Seattle[/wimpLink] under the name [wimpLink artistId="3648882"]the No W.T.O. Combo[/wimpLink].
By the late '90s, [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink] began research for a proposed box set of previously unreleased songs from throughout [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink]'s career. The project was supposed to surface in the fall of 2001 (to coincide with the tenth anniversary release of Nevermind), but legal issues delayed its release. Finally, the Nirvana LLC partnership -- which included [wimpLink artistId="5948383"]Grohl[/wimpLink], [wimpLink artistId="6425436"]Novoselic[/wimpLink], and [wimpLink artistId="11159"]Love[/wimpLink] -- came to an agreement and the album-length compilation [wimpLink albumId="92239126"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] was released in October of 2002. Although that release included only one unreleased song, the long-awaited box set, titled With the Lights Out, appeared in late 2004, including three discs of rare and unreleased material plus a live DVD that featured material filmed as early as 1988. The band's 1992 set at the Reading Festival was released in 2009 as [wimpLink albumId="3160050"]Live at Reading[/wimpLink]. The same year, Sub Pop began a [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] studio album reissue campaign with [wimpLink albumId="68639771"]Bleach[/wimpLink]; special 20th-anniversary editions of Nevermind and [wimpLink albumId="77610844"]In Utero[/wimpLink] followed in 2011 and 2013, respectively. In 2014, [wimpLink artistId="19368"]Nirvana[/wimpLink] was inducted into the Rock & Roll Hall of Fame by [wimpLink artistId="9366"]R.E.M.[/wimpLink]'s [wimpLink artistId="27443"]Michael Stipe[/wimpLink]. [wimpLink artistId="3985235"]Cobain[/wimpLink]'s place in the induction performance was taken by several vocalists, including [wimpLink artistId="3711483"]Joan Jett[/wimpLink] and [wimpLink artistId="6939914"]Kim Gordon[/wimpLink]. ~ Stephen Thomas Erlewine & Greg Prato

item.title: Nirvana Essentials
item.description: Nothing was ever quite the same after Nirvana. The band’s second album, 1991’s ‘Nevermind,’ revolutionized popular music by bringing alternative rock above ground, introducing mainstream audiences to sounds and concepts that had previously existed only in shadowy record store corners and on low-frequency college radio airwaves. ‘Nevermind’’s noisy, dissonant guitar rock, mumbled or howled surrealistic lyrics, and generally angsty punk attitudes were unlikely candidates for chart success, but the band undercut their grungy songs with enough pop melodicism to create a sound unlike anything average listeners had ever heard before, striking at the exact right moment to become an unprecedented success. Since Nirvana were rooted in an indie aesthetic but loved pop music, they fought their stardom while courting it, becoming some of the most notorious anti-rock stars in history. They consciously attempted to shed their audience with their abrasive, Steve Albini-produced third album, ‘In Utero,’ but by that point, the fate of the band and vocalist/guitarist/songwriter Kurt Cobain had been sealed. Suffering from drug addiction and manic depression, Cobain had become destructive and suicidal, though his management and label were able to hide the extent of his problems from the public until April 8, 1994, when he was found dead of a self-inflicted shotgun wound. Cobain’s death cut Nirvana’s story tragically short, but their legacy stands as one of the most influential in rock & roll history. (Photo and bio: Rovi)

item.title: Nirvana Live Essentials
item.description: One of Nirvana's most memorable live performances was its episode of MTV Unplugged, where they played everything from Nevermind cuts to songs by David Bowie and Meat Puppets. In this playlist, you'll hear tracks from that album plus music from their legendary Reading concert and 'Live at the Paramount.' (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Rolling Stone: Best Songs of All Time
item.description: In 2010, institutional music magazine Rolling Stone updated its list of the “500 Greatest Songs of All Time". Releases from ‘60s and ‘70s are the most represented, but it includes a good share of songs from all decades, all the way back to 1940. [This playlist is updated with the 2021 edition]

item.title: Alt Classics
item.description: All your favourite indie classics in one place. (Cover: Mother Love Bone celebrating the 2025 remastered versions of 'Apple' and 'Shine' / Photo: press)

item.title: Rock Party Classics
item.description: Rock and roll all night, and party every day, with these essential shout-along cuts. (Photo: Aleksandar Pasaric / Pexels)

item.title: Grunge 101
item.description: Grunge was born from an intense dislike of the ever-bombastic mainstream sheen of hair metal. The genre germinated in the late ‘80s in the Pacific Northwest, merging hardcore punk, heavy metal and noise rock to raucous results. It entered the mainstream on the backs of Nirvana and the Sub Pop label in the ‘90s, and went on to influence decades of indie-rock bands to come. Check out a selection of some of the most memorable and famous grunge artists and songs with this playlist. (Cover: Pearl Jam and Nirvana, Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Modern Rock Classics
item.description: Greatest rock songs from the 1990s, 2000s and onwards. (Cover: Oasis / Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Remember...the 1990s
item.description: What a memorable decade! R.E.M. and U2 ascended as world stars, while grunge changed many people's perception of what could top the charts. Pop-punk (Green Day, The Offspring) and Britpop (Oasis, Blur) were born, just as hip-hop was gaining traction on the charts (Jay-Z, Eminem). Many promising hitmakers would go on to have long, healthy careers, while others would never see the 2000s. But they all belong in our collective memory of the 1990's. (Cover: The Notorious B.I.G. - Ready to Die, Bad Boy/WMG)

item.title: 1990s Alternative Rock Classics
item.description: In the 1990s alternative and indie rock sprouted up from it roots in underground infancy and broke into mainstream mass culture in a big way. This playlist takes you back to that golden decade with some of the finest alternative songs from the 1990s. (Cover: Pavement Slanted & Enchanted, Matador/Beggars)

item.title: 2000s Rock Hits
item.description: A trip down memory lane to revisit some of the finest rock songs of the 2000s. Enjoy the big hits, timeless classics and forgotten favorites. (Cover: Nickelback - Silver Side Up, Roadrunner/WMG)

item.title: 1994! Songs of the Year
item.description: Relive the biggest hits, most memorable favorites and forgotten gems from 1994. [The playlist follows the rule of first release date]. (Cover: Pulp Fiction - Music From the Motion Picture, Geffen/UMG)

item.title: 1990s Rock Hits
item.description: A trip down memory lane to revisit some of the finest rock songs of the 1990s. Enjoy the big hits, timeless classics and forgotten favorites. (Cover: Pearl Jam, Epic/Sony)

item.title: 1993! Songs of the Year
item.description: Relive the biggest hits, treasured songs and forgotten favorites from 1993. [The playlist follows the rule of first release date]. (Cover: Wu-Tang Clan - Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers), RCA/Sony)

item.title: 1989! Songs of the Year
item.description: 1989 was the year the Berlin Wall started to crack open, the beginning of the Velvet Revolution in Eastern Europe and the not so peaceful Tiananmen Square protests in China. It was also a pretty good year in music, with landmark albums from major artists like Madonna, Janet Jackson and Tom Petty. This was the golden age of hip-hop, and it was the final days of mainstream hardrock before the grunge craze swept the world – introducing the world to debut full-length albums from Nirvana, Mudhoney, Tad and Soundgarden. Albums from The Pixies, The Stone Roses and Depeche Mode helped crossing the alternative into the mainstream. Listen to the sound of 1989 with this playlist, including time typical tunes, the biggest hits and some forgotten gems. [This list of yearly songs follows the rule of earliest release date.] (Cover: Madonna - Like a Prayer, Sire/Warner)

item.title: 1980s Alternative Rock Classics
item.description: The finest alternative rock songs from the 1980s, from underground favorites to timeless classics. (Cover: R.E.M. - Murmur, A&M/Universal)

item.title: 1991! Songs of the Year
item.description: Grunge, goth and gangsta rap all collided in one of the most memorable years in musical history. (Cover: Nirvana - Nevermind, Geffen/UMG)

item.title: 1980s American Underground
item.description: On the outside of 1980s mainstream culture, a pioneering and disparate contingent of misfits made up the American Underground - from hardcore punk to jangle pop. Some are sadly forgotten today, other went on to have lengthy and successful careers, but they all shaped the sound of alternative rock to come. This broad playlist gives you handpicked faves from that special time and place. (Cover: Hüsker Dü - New Day Rising, SST/The Orchard)

item.title: Rock for Beginners
item.description: New to rock? These carefully selected 20 tracks will serve as your beginner's guide to some of the best the genre has to offer. Use them as a jumping-off point to discover even more great rock.

item.title: Flannel & Fuzz: Grunge Trailblazers
item.description: In the early 1990s, Seattle and the Pacific Northwest went from being just another thriving area for underground music and culture to become the hippest music and fashion capitol of the world. This playlist takes you back to some of the artists that paved way for it all, a deep dive into the scene just before it exploded - and eventually imploded. Here are prime grunge bands in the infancy of their careers, regional pioneers and influencers further away both in time and distance playing a key role in the development of what would become a musical earthquake. (Photo: Green River / Credit: Rovi)

item.title: Murder Ballads: Stories of Misery & Mayhem
item.description:
Murder ballads have a history that goes back to pre-modern times, with many originating in England and Scotland and written down, printed and sold on broadsheets already in the 17th century as true crime novels of their time. These dark and often grotesque stories have endured during the centuries in their purest form or mutating into something slightly different as they found new life on the other side of the Atlantic with the European settlers. A classic example would be the Appalachian murder ballad “The Knoxville Girl”, which can be derived under various names back to English ballads from the 1500s. But murder is also a frequent topic in American ballads, as Library of Congress states: “Many murder ballads were composed in America, especially after famous murder cases. An example is "Pearl Bryant," a fictionalized account of the murder of Pearl Bryan in Kentucky in 1896.” This playlist is a collection of some of the most famous Murder Ballads, including “Tom Dooley”, “Stagger Lee” and “In the Pines”, as well as some more recent examples of this storytelling tradition. 
[Cover: "Anguish", Albrecht Schenck, public domain]

item.title: It's Accordion Time!
item.description: Every year, on the sixth day of May, accordion players and aficionados across the globe squeeze their bellows together in shared celebration of World Accordion Day, coordinated by the Confédération Internationale des Accordéonistes. It's distinct and versatile sound has found its way into genres and music traditions around the world. To pay our gratitude, we've made this collection of tracks either featuring great accordion players or where accordion plays a prominent role. From Arcade Fire to Edith Piaf, from indie rock to traditional folk styles like musette, klezmer, zydeco, and much more we salute the magnificent fruits of the accordion. (Photo: Unsplash)

item.title: Songs For The Deaf: Millennium Hard Rock
item.description: Classic hard rock anthems from the 1990s and early 2000s. (Cover: Rage Against the Machine / Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Hits For Kids of All Ages
item.description: Teach your children well; sing along, dance and discover the iconic classics with this (more or less chronological) playlist of artists and songs kids of all ages should know. Clean tracks only.  (Cover: TIDAL)

item.title: Autumn in Seattle
item.description: Celebrate Seattle’s game-changing rock ’n’ roll and indie heritage with this Emerald City playlist.

item.title: Sonic Paradise: Noise Rock Bonanza
item.description: Hidden in the darker corners in the grand hall of rock 'n' roll, we find some open-minded experimentalists, noise lovers and free thinkers that created music like no-one else. Revisit some of noise rock's most inventive pioneers and their followers with this playlist - from the bourgeoning '80s scene to noisemongers before and after. All in the name of noise. (Cover: Unplash)

item.title: Nirvana: Nevermind - The Story
item.description: ‘Nevermind, It’s an Interview’ was released as a limited edition, promo only interview CD by Geffen Records in 1992. The interviews were conducted by Kurt St. Thomas whilst Music Director of WFNX in Boston, MA. Krist Novoselic and Dave Grohl's contributions were recorded on January 10th 1992 (after Nirvana’s appearance on MTV's '120 Minutes') whilst Kurt Cobain's part was recorded on January 11th 1992 (after their appearance on 'Saturday Night Live’). The CD was intended for radio airplay, and never released for sale to the public. Now, you can listen to the entire recording in a newly edited version back to back with a wide selection of classic Nirvana songs from ‘Bleach’ to ‘Nevermind’. This is 'Nevermind - the Story'. (Photo: UMG, press)

item.title: Great Sounds From the Puget Sound: Kingsmen to Nirvana
item.description: Before Nirvana and the grunge craze hit the global mainstream in the early 1990s, Seattle and the greater Pacific Northwest was commonly regarded as a music backwoods region defined by isolation and bad weather. But in truth the Great Northwest has a long and unbroken lineage of rock ’n’ roll to its history, and today remains one of the finest and most creative hubs in the U.S. This playlist guides you through some great moments of Northwestern rock ’n’ roll pride, from the two anthems “Louie Louie” to “Smells Like Teen Spirit”, and beginning with '50s and '60s classics like The Ventures, The Wailers, The Sonics and Paul Revere and the Raiders who all shape the sounds of their time. Also including Seattle-born icon Jimi Hendrix (even though not based in town when he launched his solo career), the true midpoint of this tour centers around rock legends Heart, who fusion of metal and radio-friendly hard rock in the early 1970s bridges the gap between the glorious garage rock heyday and the '90s alternative rock boom. This is just a brief glimpse of what was going on, including influential bands in many directions; Mecca Normal (Vancouver, Riot Grrrl), D.O.A (Vancouver, hardcore), Wipers (Portland, DIY), Queenrÿche (Seattle, metal), Beat Happening (Olympia, lo-fi), Young Fresh Fellows (Seattle, power pop), U-Men (Seattle, grunge) and Melvins (Aberdeen, grunge). And since Nirvana, Alice in Chains, Pearl Jam and others permanently put the region on the map, it has continued to spew out an ever wider musical platter of great sounds from the Puget Sound – more than enough to fill up a sequel to this overview.  (Photo: Unsplash)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Shakira
item.description: Shakira's music draws from the most primal aspects of her Lebanese and Colombian roots, layering these sonic influences atop a foundation of rock 'n roll that stems from her long-held love of bands like the Rolling Stones, Metallica, Nirvana, and The Clash. The result has been a captivating cultural melange of musical sounds that has allowed Shakira to belly-dance her way into our hearts. (Photo: Sony)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: J Balvin
item.description: J Balvin is the face of modern day reggaeton. Yet, the Colombian superstar always pays respects to the legends of the genre (see his impressive gritty “Reggaeton,” which samples the iconic Hector El Father). In this edition of “Tracks & Traces” we pay it right back with his music influences (Daddy Yankee, Nirvana, 2Pac), his business idols (JAY-Z, Diddy, 50 Cent), his country’s best (Juanes, Shakira, Joe Arroyo) and those he’s influenced (Bad Bunny, Karol G, Rosalía). Balvin is truly a global superstar.  (Photo: UMLE)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Black Sabbath
item.description: With Tracks & Traces, we aim to expand the horizon around a given artist with related tracks and similar artists in order to present a deeper insight into their music. Black Sabbath is quite simply one of the most popular, groundbreaking and influential bands ever. Formed in Birmingham in the late 1960s and inspired by blues-rock of the time (Cream, Blue Cheer), Sabbath are the undisputed gods of heavy metal, the living legends that, better than anyone else, mixed the toughest blues with the heaviest rock. Along the way they not only created a template for the whole genre, but influenced numerous variations of hard rock over the years including doom metal, grunge, sludge metal and much more. This playlist gives a glimpse into their massive legacy. (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Neil Young
item.description: As the man who started out with folk-rock and came to be known as the "Godfather of Grunge," Neil Young and has tried out almost everything over his long, eventful career. With his distinctive songwriting and guitar sound, and his one-of-a-kind voice, Neil Young sounds like no one else, and his tremendous influence can be traced to a countless marching band of artists. This playlist is an attempt to honor Neil Young through the lenses of artists who owe, to a larger or smaller degree, some palpable musical debt to the master himself, both directly (in terms of cover songs) and more subtle in terms of sound and songwriting. It’s a highly enjoyable playlist in his own right, covering some of the finest songwriters from the 1960s and onward. From Hank to Hendrix and beyond. (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: The Velvet Underground

promotedArtists.name: David Bowie & The Spiders From Mars

item.description: The Velvet Underground have an invaluable influence on music that can’t be understated. What The Beatles did for pop and mainstream rock, The Velvet Underground did for punk, post-punk, art-rock, grunge, and every variation of alternative, indie and experimental rock. We honor the band’s extreme legacy with just a couple of examples of their tracks and their traces. (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: David Bowie
item.description: With Tracks & Traces we aim to expand the horizon around a given artist, with related tracks and similar artists, in order to present a deeper insight into their music through the lenses and mirrors of others. David Bowie is surely hard to pigeonhole, thanks to a lifetime of innovation, invention and so many different phases. Bowie has been a tremendous force of influence in countless ways, and it’s impossible to grasp it all in one reasonably-sized playlist — there’s a vast musical landscape between his mod roots in the late '60s to getting inspired by Kendrick Lamar 50 years later — and this playlist reveals just a small slice of his groundbreaking legacy. (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Slint
item.description:
With their odd time signatures, innovative use of soft-loud dynamics and intricate guitar work, Louisville, Kentucky’s Slint sounded like almost no-one else at the time. Their complex and compelling landmark album ‘Spiderland’ (1991) was a gateway to modern rock, whether it was being labelled as post-rock, math-rock, post-hardcore and other sub-genres. Slint fragmented into numerous different bands post ’Spiderland’, but 30 years down the road the album sounds as fresh and vital as ever. This playlist is an attempt to grasp the musical universe of Slint through the lense of other artists. 

Tracks & Traces aims to expand the horizon around a given artist with related tracks and similar artists in order to present a deeper insight into the past, present and future of their music. (Photo: Secretly Canadian, press)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Weezer
item.description: With Tracks & Traces, we aim to expand the horizon around a given artist with related tracks and similar artists in order to present a deeper insight into their music. Weezer's impact on the sound of the '90s transcends commercial and independent music. The quartet's tendency toward expansive, arena-friendly hooks landed the band multiple commercially successful hits. This radio-friendly sound was, however, born out of their quaint, twee beginnings. Twenty-five years after the release of their first record, the group is still a conduit for pop-leaning rock of all forms, bridging the power pop of the '80s and the winsome pop of the '90s and '00s. (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Half Japanese
item.description: Lo-fi indie-rock favorites Half Japanese have enjoyed a massive cult status, almost since their humble bedroom beginnings in the mid-1970s. Centered around brothers Jad & David Fair, they’ve never broke even close into the mainstream, preferring to dance to the unique beat of their own off-rhythm drum. Rather by spearheading the lo-fi and D.I.Y. movement, Half Japanese have been a major influence to such bands as Sonic Youth, Neutral Milk Hotel and Kurt Cobain who ranked them among his very favorites, chose them to open for Nirvana on the In Utero tour and was even wearing their T-shirt when he died. Over the years, Jad and David Fair have collaborated with loads of like-minded artists and friends, including Daniel Johnston, Teenage Fanclub, Yo La Tengo and John Zorn, all being a part of their universe. This playlist pays tribute to Half Japanese, by chasing their tracks & traces. (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Foo Fighters
item.description: With songs like 1997’s “Everlong” and 2005’s “Best of You,” Foo Fighters proved themselves to be one of the greatest anthemic rock groups of all time. In this Tracks & Traces playlist, you’ll journey with the band from the past to the future. You’ll hear the music they made before Foo Fighters (Nirvana, Germs), the sounds they were listening to on their way up (Black Sabbath, Led Zeppelin), their '90s contemporaries (Pearl Jam, Alice in Chains), and the artists they paved the way for (Arcade Fire, Florence + the Machine). (Photo: Rovi)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Romeo Santos
item.description: By infusing hip-hop and R&B influences into traditional bachata, Romeo Santos managed to breathe new life into a musical genre that, for years, had been relegated to the Dominican Republic's countryside. Both as Aventura's frontman and, later, as a solo act, Santos has brought a streetwise swagger to his performances — all while wooing audiences with his high falsetto and peppering his Spanish lyrics with flirtatious English catchphrases like "So nasty" and "You like it, baby?" We do indeed. (Photo: Sony)

item.title: Tracks & Traces: Patti Smith
item.description: Tracks & Traces reflects on a legendary artist’s influences and cultural milieu as well as the sounds and aesthetics that followed them. This is a tribute to punk rock icon, poet, rebel and rock‘n roll powerhouse Patti Smith. (Photo: Rovi)
